I love watching your videos! My name is Ben Novick, and I'm the local private investigator on the Big Island of Hawaii. We have all of the climates of the world and since the pandemic have experienced an interesting time surviving without many tourists, but it's extra beautiful. Here, we have little to no crime as we use to experience in Los Angeles where I came from 22 years ago. The island is 184 miles around, with 170K people, two volcanoes and 5 Covid cases last week. Here, my jobs have mainly been security for entertainment people who come here to escape civilization. A couple of stalkers have even tried to purse people here, but were unsuccessful. I have friends who are dogs, mongooses, a drake (male) Perin duck named "Donald" and a black Astrolarp hen named "sparkle." She lays me one big brown egg each morning, leaving it on a chair outside my front door.
We are totally self sufficient. While I don't often eat red meat, we have cows, goats, sheep and a mass of wild boar and all the fish you could desire.
If you like mangoes, strawberry papayas, and coconuts you may eat them to your heart's desire in addition to many other varieties of tropical fruit, including Suriname cherries. All vegetables grow here but carrots and potatoes need to be grown in a soil garden because much of the ground is lava rock. My latest job has been taking a few locals on UFO tours. Since the pandemic we have been seeing lots of them, and I had one startling experience when I pointed a flashlight at one and it came to us--scared my guests to the point when I looked around they were gone. But, I sense they mean us no harm. If ever here, feel free to look me up! Favorite spots are the black sand beach, Akaka falls, rain forest, an observatory, the volcanoes park and caves. Thanks for sharing your wonderful explorations! Have a good evening.

Yep, that is Jolly Quarzo - a 240m long ship from Messina Line Company. By the way, her ship is Ad Astra (70m long) so she overestimated the size. In reality, all deep water vessels look huge when compared to what people normally see on land. At open sea, you cannot easily compare it to anything around you so people tend to disorientate and delude themselves about sizes and distances. They always assume ship/land is closer and bigger than it really is. For example, 1 nautical mile (1.852km) really looks like 100m when at sea.
